<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-079-912  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 079 912.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Feb 27 1989 v23 n8 p8(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Customs net seals U.S. border. (US Customs Consolidated DataNetwork) (US-Mexico border)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Horwitt, Elisabeth.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Customs Consolidated Data Network is an upgrade of the19-year-old Customs Law Enforcement system that links borderstations and agents with the Customs Service's data center nearWashington, DC.andP;  The system lets the agents know whether thevehicle approaching their station is likely to contain a harmlesstourist, an armed drug runner or possibly a fleeing white-collarcriminal.andP;  The San Diego-based system contains records from theBureau of Motor Vehicles.andP;  The network now has some 3,000terminals and serves the entire US-Mexican border includingairports.andP;  The San Diego data center is being consolidated underthe wing of central information systems to save about $1.75million annually.andP;  Datacom-DB software runs on a NationalSemiconductor NAS XL-100 mainframe; all of Customs, the IRS,Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms and some Treasury agencies will beon the network by the end of 1989.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Customs ServiceNetworksLaw EnforcementNational GovernmentApplications.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>